proof_block:
// The previous attempt asserted things like `post1_proc_perm@.is_init()`
// directly. Those asserts failed because the antecedent of the ensures
// implication (the big `&&&` chain of post1/post2 ensures) is NOT in the
// proof-context when Verus checks an intermediate `assert` — only the
// `requires` clauses are. So intermediate asserts on `post*_proc_perm`
// are not derivable. The repair is to (a) only assert facts derivable
// from `requires` and (b) inject the relational axioms about
// `Seq::remove_value` and `no_duplicates` that z3 needs to chain
// `post1.children@ =~= pre.children@.remove_value(child)` with the
// symmetric ensures for `post2` into `post1.children@ == post2.children@`
// once the implication antecedent IS in scope (at the function-exit
// ensures check).
//
// All statements below are provable from the function `requires` alone
// (plus the lemma ensures we explicitly invoke); none of them touches
// `post1_proc_perm` or `post2_proc_perm`.

// (1) Bring the `Seq::remove_value` axioms into scope. The lemma's ensures
//     are universally quantified — calling it makes the forall fact
//     available unconditionally.
seq_remove_lemma::<ProcPtr>();
seq_remove_lemma_2::<ProcPtr>();

// (2) pre.children is `unique() && wf()` from requires, which gives us
//     `pre.children@.no_duplicates()` via the library lemma. This is the
//     hypothesis seq_remove_lemma_2's clauses need to fire.
pre_proc_perm@.value().children.unique_implys_no_duplicates();
assert(pre_proc_perm@.value().children@.no_duplicates());

// (3) Concrete instantiation of seq_remove_lemma_2's second clause on
//     the specific sequence and value the ensures actually mention. This
//     plants a trigger on `pre.children@.remove_value(child_proc_ptr@)`
//     that z3 can match against the `post1.children@ =~= ...` and
//     `post2.children@ =~= ...` ensures conjuncts.
assert(!pre_proc_perm@.value().children@
    .remove_value(child_proc_ptr@).contains(child_proc_ptr@));

// (4) The pre.children sequence contains the child we are about to remove
//     (this is in requires); re-stating it pins the witness so the
//     `s.contains(v) && s[i] == v && s.no_duplicates() ==>
//      s.subrange(0,i).add(s.subrange(i+1,len)) == s.remove_value(v)`
//     branch of seq_remove_lemma can be instantiated.
assert(pre_proc_perm@.value().children@.contains(child_proc_ptr@));
